Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp} for the orzo. Trim the @asparagus{100%g} and chop into thirds widthways. Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice.

Pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and halve the @lemon{1}.

Once the pan of water is boiling, add the @orzo{180%g}, reduce the heat to medium and cook until just tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Add the asparagus for the final ~{3%minutes} of cooking.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and half the @unsalted butter{30%g} in a large saucepan on medium heat. Once hot, add the sliced leek and cook, stirring, until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}. Add the @water{some} and @vegetable stock powder{1%tsp}. Stir to dissolve the stock, lower the heat and simmer until reduced by half, ~{2%minutes}.

When the orzo and asparagus are done, allow it to drain really well. Add the orzo and asparagus to the leek pan, stir it through then add the @baby spinach{125%g}. Keep stirring until the spinach has wilted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Now stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g}, @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, remaining butter, lemon zest and a squeeze of lemon juice - keep stirring!

> TIP: The more you stir, the creamier the orzo will become!

Cook for another ~{2%minutes} then remove the pan from the heat.

> TIP: Stir in a splash more hot water if it seems a bit dry - you are looking for the consistency of risotto!

Stir the chopped mint through the orzo. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and add more lemon juice if you like.

Divide the orzotto between #bowls{} and top with the @walnuts{20%g}. Enjoy!